07263nam a22010095i 9780812203509DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20122009pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979753705  a97808122035097 a10.9783/97808122035092doi  a(DE-B1597)449185  a(OCoLC)802049501  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHM1271b.C853 2009eb 7aPOL0380002bisacsh04a305.822200aCulture and Belonging in Divided Societies :bContestation and Symbolic Landscapes /ced. by Marc Howard Ross. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2012] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b11 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter 1. Cultural Contestation and the Symbolic Landscape -- tChapter 2. The Rise and Fall of a Sacred Place -- tChapter 3. Social Lives of the Dead -- tChapter 4. Flagging Peace -- tChapter 5. Conflict Transformation, Cultural Innovation, and Loyalist Identity in Northern Ireland -- tChapter 6. Islamic Headscarves in Public Schools -- tChapter 7. Minority Language Policy in France -- tChapter 8. Symbols of Reconciliation or Instruments of Division? -- tChapter 9. Emerging Multiculturalisms in South African Museum Practice -- tChapter 10. Strategies for Transforming and Enlarging South Africa’s Post-Apartheid Symbolic Landscape -- tChapter 11. Invisible House, Invisible Slavery -- tChapter 12. Politicizing Chinese New Year Festivals -- tChapter 13. Paddy, Shylock, and Sambo -- tEpilogue -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom cartoons of Muhammad in a Danish newspaper to displays of the Confederate battle flag over the South Carolina statehouse, acts of cultural significance have set off political conflicts and sometimes violence. These and other expressions and enactments of culture—whether in music, graffiti, sculpture, flag displays, parades, religious rituals, or film—regularly produce divisive and sometimes prolonged disputes. What is striking about so many of these conflicts is their emotional intensity, despite the fact that in many cases what is at stake is often of little material value. Why do people invest so much emotional energy and resources in such conflicts? What is at stake, and what does winning or losing represent? The answers to these questions explored in Culture and Belonging in Divided Societies view cultural expressions variously as barriers to, or opportunities for, inclusion in a divided society's symbolic landscape and political life.Though little may be at stake materially, deep emotional investment in conflicts over cultural acts can have significant political consequences. At the same time, while cultural issues often exacerbate conflict, new or redefined cultural expressions and enactments can redirect long-standing conflicts in more constructive directions and promote reconciliation in ways that lead to or reinforce formal peace agreements. Encompassing work by a diverse group of scholars of American studies, anthropology, art history, religion, political science, and other fields, Culture and Belonging in Divided Societies addresses the power of cultural expressions and enactments in highly charged settings, exploring when and how changes in a society's symbolic landscape occur and what this tells us about political life in the societies in which they take place.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCultural pluralism. 0aMulticulturalism. 0aPOLITICAL SCIENCEvPublic PolicyvCultural Policy. 0aSymbolism. 4aFolklore. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Cultural Policy.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aFolklore.  aLinguistics.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.1 aBryan, Domini